1
00:00:03,136 --> 00:00:07,062
Daily life, the noble eightfold path.

2
00:00:07,081 --> 00:00:18,701
As the retreat comes to an end, we naturally start to think about the bigger picture, family, friends, work and so on, and how we might bring the benefits of our retreat practice into everyday life.

3
00:00:20,243 --> 00:00:29,277
To get the Buddha's advice on this, we have the fourth noble truth, the path to the end of suffering, with the injunction to follow this path for ourselves.

4
00:00:30,541 --> 00:00:35,490
The path itself has eight strands and is known as the Noble Eightfold Path.

5
00:00:36,011 --> 00:00:40,378
Noble because it is ennobling and it makes for a worthy life.

6
00:00:41,018 --> 00:00:46,609
I'd been meditating for a few years before I really started taking this Eightfold Path to heart.

7
00:00:47,250 --> 00:00:52,780
Earlier I'd been so intent on learning to meditate I didn't take much notice of anything else in Buddhism.

8
00:00:53,401 --> 00:00:55,484
But finally the penny dropped.

9
00:00:55,685 --> 00:01:03,801
I realised there was so much more I could do, that there were lots of areas of life that could open up as part of spiritual practice.

10
00:01:03,822 --> 00:01:05,865
It was a great relief to realise this.

11
00:01:06,367 --> 00:01:08,512
I felt empowered and inspired.

12
00:01:09,313 --> 00:01:13,962
I hope it doesn't take any of you so long to open up to this teaching.

13
00:01:15,260 --> 00:01:21,572
Each of the strands is described as right, right view, right attitude and so on.

14
00:01:22,233 --> 00:01:25,939
This can be off-putting as if there's no room for discussion or error.

15
00:01:26,540 --> 00:01:32,492
In practice, much of the path has to be discovered by trial and error, by considering

16
00:01:32,471 --> 00:01:35,415
by experimenting, learning and discussing.

17
00:01:36,197 --> 00:01:38,561
But we're not in a sea of confusion either.

18
00:01:38,980 --> 00:01:46,152
We have these eight signposts to give us a sense of direction, a basis on which to learn and question and discuss.

19
00:01:47,254 --> 00:01:50,959
It starts with right view or right understanding.

20
00:01:50,978 --> 00:02:00,673
This sounds dogmatic and the Buddha wasn't shy about stating his views as right, true, correct, while also saying that we have to investigate,

21
00:02:01,058 --> 00:02:05,525
see for ourselves whether they hold true in our own experience also.

22
00:02:06,466 --> 00:02:11,395
It's not a path of pure faith that we're following, but a path of wisdom.

23
00:02:12,556 --> 00:02:17,403
Any form of Dhamma study will strengthen this aspect of the Eightfold Path.

24
00:02:18,105 --> 00:02:23,995
There are so many good books and after the retreat we'll provide a short list of some of our favourites.

25
00:02:24,362 --> 00:02:34,372
Or you could sign up for a magazine like Tricycle, which gives daily Dhamma bites into your email inbox and lots of excellent articles.

26
00:02:36,073 --> 00:02:37,473
Listen to Dhamma talks.

27
00:02:37,995 --> 00:02:40,296
Again, there are thousands to choose from.

28
00:02:40,836 --> 00:02:53,407
We have many on the Satipanya website and an excellent resource is the website Dhamma Seed, which has all the Gaia House talks, as well as those from IMS and other meditation centres.

29
00:02:54,028 --> 00:02:55,712
You could join a study program.

30
00:02:56,074 --> 00:03:07,223
There are many online courses available, including one that I offer twice a year at Sati Panya, usually lasting around six weeks and based on some aspect of the Dhamma.

31
00:03:07,243 --> 00:03:10,552
Could be the four foundations for mindfulness, for example.

32
00:03:11,629 --> 00:03:27,016
Each week there are a set of notes with suggested exercises and people post their observations and reflections on a forum which gives way to learn from one another, which can often seem more believable than when it comes from a teacher.

33
00:03:27,737 --> 00:03:34,650
And Carl offers an online study programme, meeting monthly on Zoom to meditate and discuss the Dharma.

34
00:03:35,508 --> 00:03:45,697
The second strand of the path is right attitude, which means cultivating an attitude of goodwill in the forms of compassion, generosity, kindness.

35
00:03:46,457 --> 00:03:50,681
For this, we have the practice of goodwill meditation, metta.

36
00:03:51,602 --> 00:03:59,469
It's a good habit to finish daily meditation with about 10 minutes of metta and listen to a guided metta practice regularly.

37
00:04:00,310 --> 00:04:05,514
Bhante Bodhidharma has one you can download from the Satipanya website, for example.

38
00:04:05,495 --> 00:04:08,938
And there are hundreds to choose from on Dhamma Seed.

39
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:14,466
We can also get into the habit of making good wishes regularly throughout the day.

40
00:04:15,287 --> 00:04:20,915
For example, if you're meeting with someone, spend a moment beforehand wishing them well in your heart.

41
00:04:21,696 --> 00:04:25,139
I'm sure you will find the meetings far more meaningful if you do that.

42
00:04:25,593 --> 00:04:32,459
As you go into a meeting at work, make a good wish that this will benefit the organisation, the people you serve.

43
00:04:33,379 --> 00:04:36,762
As you're sitting on a bus, you can wish well to those around you.

44
00:04:38,184 --> 00:04:49,173
I was on a loving kindness retreat with Sharon Salzberg, a renowned teacher, and she advised taking walks in nature, wishing well to the trees and bushes as we pass.

45
00:04:49,913 --> 00:04:50,995
A lovely practice.

46
00:04:51,956 --> 00:04:55,278
I went through a very brief knitting craze a few years ago,

47
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:59,047
And for every stitch I'd make a good wish for someone.

48
00:04:59,067 --> 00:05:04,656
There are no end of variations to the formal meta practice and it's good fun trying them out.

49
00:05:05,699 --> 00:05:06,880
A word of warning though.

50
00:05:07,601 --> 00:05:12,430
All the hindrances we come across in Vipassana show up just as often in meta.

51
00:05:13,432 --> 00:05:17,720
Sometimes we can't stop daydreaming, planning, writing a bestseller.

52
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:19,983
Other times a version shows up.

53
00:05:20,437 --> 00:05:22,560
We feel resentful instead of friendly.

54
00:05:23,261 --> 00:05:28,286
Else we doze off or get all fidgety and worried, or doubt this is doing any good to anyone.

55
00:05:29,048 --> 00:05:38,641
It's easy to compound the difficulty by assuming we must be a hard-hearted, mean-spirited person, incapable of love, totally unlovable.

56
00:05:39,362 --> 00:05:49,194
Instead, we should simply acknowledge that there's a hindrance afoot, and that we need to take it easy, be mindful for a while, rather than pressing ourselves for good wishes.

57
00:05:50,930 --> 00:06:01,802
After a while, it may be possible to return to Meta, but at a gentler pace, maybe a good wish at every third or fourth tree, every tenth passenger on the bus.

58
00:06:03,324 --> 00:06:08,730
Meta can be incredibly effective at repairing a bad relationship.

59
00:06:08,750 --> 00:06:13,596
I got off to a bad start with one particular colleague and dreaded every encounter.

60
00:06:14,487 --> 00:06:20,812
A friend reminded me to bring him to mind and say, may you be well, as I went about my other tasks.

61
00:06:21,694 --> 00:06:26,478
It might have helped that he went on a fortnight's holiday when I started this practice.

62
00:06:26,499 --> 00:06:30,502
But when he came back, I found myself relating to him quite easily.

63
00:06:31,264 --> 00:06:37,750
And in fact, we became friends as well as enjoying an easy and productive working relationship.

64
00:06:37,769 --> 00:06:43,836
This strand of the Eightfold Path, Right Attitude, brings a lot of happiness into life.

65
00:06:45,250 --> 00:06:58,151
The next three strands of the path concern morality, sila in Pali, but before going through these, I want to show the role of kame here, how it links morality and happiness.

66
00:06:59,834 --> 00:07:09,992
When we hear of someone's good fortune, we might say, oh, that's your good kame, and we might think along the same lines for misfortune, but this is a mistake.

67
00:07:10,326 --> 00:07:14,673
The Buddha said that karma was one of five laws operating in the universe.

68
00:07:15,434 --> 00:07:24,446
As well as the law of karma, we have the laws of the physical world, biology, psychology and finally the dharma, the four noble truths.

69
00:07:25,348 --> 00:07:29,293
We cannot ascribe someone's injury or handicap to bad karma.

70
00:07:29,834 --> 00:07:32,858
It could be due to biology, could be due to physics.

71
00:07:33,495 --> 00:07:37,701
Nor can we ascribe their beauty or longevity to good karma.

72
00:07:38,141 --> 00:07:40,603
These could be the biology of inheritance.

73
00:07:41,805 --> 00:07:47,391
What we can ascribe to their previous karma is a person's happiness or unhappiness.

74
00:07:48,333 --> 00:07:50,836
These operate under the law of karma.

75
00:07:51,516 --> 00:08:01,848
When we think, speak or act motivated by greed, hatred or delusion, we sow karma seeds, which will eventually ripen to diminish our happiness.

76
00:08:02,572 --> 00:08:08,180
Conversely, thoughts of goodwill sow seeds of karma that ripen to make us happier.

77
00:08:08,862 --> 00:08:11,185
Sometimes the connection can be easily seen.

78
00:08:11,987 --> 00:08:17,735
For example, if we decide to give someone a present, then even the thought of this makes us feel happy.

79
00:08:18,516 --> 00:08:30,435
Often the process isn't immediate and can be quite subtle, so it can perhaps take years of careful observation to convince ourselves of the law of karma.

80
00:08:31,089 --> 00:08:34,158
but we can see how it happens in broad terms.

81
00:08:35,802 --> 00:08:40,154
Motivated by ill will, we say something nasty.

82
00:08:40,490 --> 00:08:43,452
We might feel strong as a result, get our own way.

83
00:08:44,014 --> 00:08:46,176
So we get in the habit of nasty speech.

84
00:08:46,796 --> 00:08:50,259
Each callous remark confirms our position of power.

85
00:08:51,120 --> 00:08:53,744
But where does it lead in the longer term?

86
00:08:54,464 --> 00:08:59,208
Those of a kind and friendly nature avoid us or confront us openly.

87
00:08:59,990 --> 00:09:09,940
More fearful or conniving people, who like being on the good side of a bully, rally around, but will be delighted to stab us in the back when they get the opportunity.

88
00:09:10,476 --> 00:09:12,659
We don't have real friends.

89
00:09:13,280 --> 00:09:18,769
Deep down we know that, and so we live in a state of suppressed anxiety.

90
00:09:18,789 --> 00:09:30,407
Similarly for greed, the enjoyment is temporary, while the stress of continually needing to satisfy our every need is exhausting, while overconsumption harms our bodies.

91
00:09:31,389 --> 00:09:36,956
And everything we consume has to be paid for, so we get stressed out with overwork.

92
00:09:37,628 --> 00:09:41,432
Satiating greed makes us feel needy rather than satisfied.

93
00:09:42,355 --> 00:09:51,888
On the other hand, if we speak or act out of goodwill, there will be social benefits as others respond warmly to generosity and kindness.

94
00:09:52,808 --> 00:09:55,052
The benefits also go deep within.

95
00:09:55,111 --> 00:09:58,636
Each kind word helps heal our own heart.

96
00:09:59,177 --> 00:10:02,842
Each act of generosity counters our sense of neediness.

97
00:10:04,561 --> 00:10:08,706
It is the motivation that matters for the law of karma.

98
00:10:08,725 --> 00:10:20,900
If a doctor cares for their patients only because of the status of the job and the amount they can charge, they suffer the consequences of greed, no matter how many people they cure.

99
00:10:22,682 --> 00:10:32,475
Because morality, sila, leads to happiness, we're not punishing ourselves by restraining our speech, actions or sexual behaviour.

100
00:10:32,759 --> 00:10:39,087
We're seeing that it's in our own best interest to speak and act with consideration for others.

101
00:10:40,529 --> 00:10:46,197
The Buddha divides Sila into three sections, right speech, action and livelihood.

102
00:10:47,198 --> 00:10:54,750
Right speech must be kindly, truthful, timely and useful, as well as being said gently rather than harshly.

103
00:10:55,809 --> 00:11:01,158
Sounds heavy going, as though you would have to think for 10 minutes before saying anything.

104
00:11:01,178 --> 00:11:15,202
But as mindfulness practice steepens and we become more sensitive to subtle emotions, the rules become internalised as a gut feeling, because speech that doesn't meet these criteria leaves us feeling bad.

105
00:11:15,942 --> 00:11:23,211
If we tell a lie, for example, some anxiety immediately starts up because there's always a danger we'll be cut out.

106
00:11:24,094 --> 00:11:35,789
Shouting and swearing at someone might give some satisfaction when we're angry, but we find it much harder to let go of the anger afterwards and we'll probably come around to regretting our loss of temper.

107
00:11:37,011 --> 00:11:44,682
Idle gossip gives the thrill of titillation, but at our next meditation, we probably find our mind full of restless thoughts.

108
00:11:45,591 --> 00:11:50,999
On investigation, we see they link to regret, having spoken of someone behind their back.

109
00:11:52,561 --> 00:11:55,063
That's the trouble with practising mindfulness.

110
00:11:55,524 --> 00:11:58,489
We just can't get away with bad behaviour anymore.

111
00:11:59,289 --> 00:12:05,557
It's because our nature is only at peace with itself when we're speaking and acting out of goodwill.

112
00:12:06,144 --> 00:12:18,880
The meanness or subtle cruelty that so easily accompanies lies or harsh speech or gossip grates against our true nature, gives us a hard time at meditation.

113
00:12:18,900 --> 00:12:21,725
Speech is useful if it promotes happiness.

114
00:12:22,485 --> 00:12:25,028
You might wonder about small talk.

115
00:12:25,048 --> 00:12:29,234
How useful can it be to talk about the weather when we all know it's raining?

116
00:12:30,014 --> 00:12:32,337
But remember, it's the motivation that counts.

117
00:12:32,960 --> 00:12:36,744
Small talk promotes friendliness, helps us feel at ease.

118
00:12:37,445 --> 00:12:38,466
Very useful.

119
00:12:39,528 --> 00:12:43,972
The main temptation towards unhelpful speech is gossip in the form of slander.

120
00:12:45,014 --> 00:12:51,500
Sometimes it can be difficult to draw the line between this and the genuine need to discuss a third party's behaviour.

121
00:12:52,282 --> 00:12:58,308
It could be because we've been hurt by the person and we need a kindly ear to help us move on.

122
00:12:58,288 --> 00:13:03,302
It could be because we've witnessed behaviour we judge as wrong and were troubled by this.

123
00:13:05,028 --> 00:13:13,732
The historian Yuval Noah Harari argues that the main purpose for language development in early humans was so that they could gossip.

124
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:24,894
This gave the tribe an advantage because if one of their members was untrustworthy, the rest of the tribe needed to know this, otherwise they couldn't maintain social cohesion.

125
00:13:25,956 --> 00:13:33,388
If your motive is to do some good by relating a tale about a third party, then this isn't idle gossip or slander.

126
00:13:33,868 --> 00:13:36,952
You're protecting others from hurt or fraud.

127
00:13:37,472 --> 00:13:39,655
But we often have mixed motives.

128
00:13:39,676 --> 00:13:51,870
As well as the genuine wish to prevent harm, there could be strains of anger and vengeance mixed in with the gleeful titillation of speaking ill of someone behind their back.

129
00:13:51,890 --> 00:14:01,703
When I sense mixed motives in this or any other aspect of Sila, then I make a good wish of the form, may I do more good than harm here.

130
00:14:02,283 --> 00:14:04,307
May I learn from any mistake.

131
00:14:06,024 --> 00:14:11,110
Ideally, we'd confront the person directly rather than tell others of their behaviour.

132
00:14:11,932 --> 00:14:16,336
But this may not always be practical and might do more harm than good.

133
00:14:18,360 --> 00:14:22,965
Timely speech is especially important when we have something difficult to say.

134
00:14:23,024 --> 00:14:27,831
Maybe you need to tell the person how hurt you were by something they did or said.

135
00:14:28,384 --> 00:14:32,491
If the other person looks exhausted or preoccupied, best hold back.

136
00:14:32,993 --> 00:14:35,977
It's easy for negativity to spread like a virus.

137
00:14:37,039 --> 00:14:44,533
It would be better to ask them to meet to discuss something sensitive so that they would be more prepared for a genuine heart to heart.

138
00:14:46,596 --> 00:14:52,586
Right action means not harming others, stealing their property or hurting through sexuality.

139
00:14:54,371 --> 00:15:05,379
While most of us would not want to kill or harm others, there is often some form of exploitation involved in the ways our food, clothing, gadgets and other goods are produced.

140
00:15:05,399 --> 00:15:11,335
In fact, it's impossible to be totally non-harming if you look into the matter seriously.

141
00:15:11,904 --> 00:15:29,288
But we can minimise harm by strategies such as purchasing ethically produced goods, avoiding factory farmed produce, becoming vegetarian or vegan, or becoming active in causes that support human rights, combat exploitation and poverty.

142
00:15:30,850 --> 00:15:31,653
Not stealing.

143
00:15:32,833 --> 00:15:36,820
Few people who come on retreat will be involved in gross theft.

144
00:15:36,840 --> 00:15:40,544
But are we using more than our fair share of the earth's resources?

145
00:15:41,133 --> 00:15:47,964
Every manufactured item, every flight, every motorised journey adds to our carbon footprint.

146
00:15:48,524 --> 00:15:49,625
Are these justified?

147
00:15:49,645 --> 00:15:51,389
Do they benefit me?

148
00:15:51,428 --> 00:15:53,072
Do they benefit others?

149
00:15:53,913 --> 00:15:58,480
A challenging question for most of us, one we need to revisit regularly.

150
00:16:00,403 --> 00:16:04,710
And then there's the thorny question of sexual behaviour.

151
00:16:04,927 --> 00:16:13,357
Sexual energy is powerful and can forge and maintain strong relationships, which might in turn sustain a family, a community.

152
00:16:14,539 --> 00:16:17,023
The benefits can spread far afield.

153
00:16:17,783 --> 00:16:22,950
On the flip side, infidelity can destroy all that, cause enormous hurt.

154
00:16:24,131 --> 00:16:24,893
Abortion

155
00:16:25,581 --> 00:16:28,227
How can we gauge the potential for suffering here?

156
00:16:28,288 --> 00:16:38,712
In Buddhist understanding, the fetus becomes conscious at the moment of conception, leaving no doubt that abortion is suffering from the fetus's point of view.

157
00:16:39,384 --> 00:16:46,658
But what suffering would be inflicted on a pregnant woman without the support and resources needed to bring a child into the world?

158
00:16:47,480 --> 00:16:48,982
No easy answers there.

159
00:16:49,844 --> 00:16:59,621
And we have the horrors of childhood sexual abuse and vulnerable people being manipulated into giving sexual favours or forced into prostitution.

160
00:17:01,542 --> 00:17:13,103
Sexuality has the potential to enhance life, to bring great joy, to underpin social cohesion, but it can also cause enormous suffering.

161
00:17:13,884 --> 00:17:21,136
There will be big questions for many of us at some stage in life, which relationship to pursue, which to forego.

162
00:17:21,876 --> 00:17:27,788
but also more subtle questions such as, am I being friendly here or am I flirting?

163
00:17:27,807 --> 00:17:40,611
In a monastic setting, lay people are asked to dress modestly and not to wear makeup as a way of waking us up to the potential for manipulating others by accentuating our sexual allure.

164
00:17:43,003 --> 00:17:46,294
The final strand of morality is right livelihood.

165
00:17:46,555 --> 00:17:54,819
The Buddha considered it wrong to make a living by dealing with weapons, poisons, slavery, intoxicants and meat.

166
00:17:55,609 --> 00:18:02,018
Although few poisons are sold legally nowadays, there is the tricky area of pest control.

167
00:18:02,578 --> 00:18:10,229
If your work involves these, see whether you could stock a compassionate alternative, like traps that do not kill the animal.

168
00:18:11,210 --> 00:18:19,119
Butchery obviously involves great suffering for animals, and there can be long, frightening journeys before slaughter.

169
00:18:19,775 --> 00:18:27,945
To be directly involved in this must be a challenge to a sensitive heart and could foster indifference, even cruelty.

170
00:18:28,846 --> 00:18:32,112
Raising animals for slaughter is part of the same business.

171
00:18:32,893 --> 00:18:41,224
The Buddha's advice is to get out of this aspect of farming and anything else to do with the meat trade for your own spiritual welfare.

172
00:18:42,686 --> 00:18:49,596
Many people are employed in the weapons industry, from soldiers on the ground to scientists in the lab.

173
00:18:50,335 --> 00:18:53,082
War seems horrific when seen from a distance.

174
00:18:53,784 --> 00:18:56,691
But can you stand by as atrocities are committed?

175
00:18:57,432 --> 00:18:59,798
It's a question of choosing the lesser evil.

176
00:19:01,343 --> 00:19:05,913
Bante has an essay, Is Armed Intervention Ever Justified?

177
00:19:06,484 --> 00:19:12,537
It's on the Satipaña website and here he distinguishes between force and violence.

178
00:19:13,538 --> 00:19:17,567
Force is the energy used to put right what is wrong.

179
00:19:18,509 --> 00:19:23,739
Violence is the same energy laced with anger, revenge, spite and so on.

180
00:19:24,460 --> 00:19:26,805
Again, it's back to motivation.

181
00:19:27,865 --> 00:19:38,095
The injunction not to deal with intoxicants poses hard questions, as almost every shop, restaurant and hotel is expected to supply alcohol.

182
00:19:39,215 --> 00:19:42,799
Most of us know people who live good lives while drinking moderately.

183
00:19:43,500 --> 00:19:50,948
On the other hand, many road accidents are alcohol related, as well as domestic and street violence and sexual abuse.

184
00:19:52,048 --> 00:19:54,530
If we can change job, then best do this.

185
00:19:55,102 --> 00:20:00,893
But that might bring its own problems if we let our family down or slide into unemployment and poverty.

186
00:20:02,095 --> 00:20:08,547
Much of the hard work with CELA is to decide which of our various options implies the lesser harm.

187
00:20:09,407 --> 00:20:14,577
For each of us, there will be difficult ethical questions to face at some stage in life.

188
00:20:15,419 --> 00:20:21,606
We need a clear mind to find the appropriate response and a stout heart to meet the challenge.

189
00:20:22,287 --> 00:20:30,657
We also need to be patient with our many mistakes, not torment ourselves about them, but remember we can learn to do better.

190
00:20:32,400 --> 00:20:36,924
The last section of the Eightfold Path concerns meditation practice.

191
00:20:38,106 --> 00:20:44,193
This also has three strands, right effort, mindfulness and concentration.

192
00:20:45,440 --> 00:20:48,911
Every step we've looked at so far requires effort.

193
00:20:49,512 --> 00:20:54,910
The effort to speak truthfully, the effort to act kindly and so on.

194
00:20:56,307 --> 00:21:04,380
It's also singled out as a factor of the Eightfold Path because we can cultivate this quality in our meditation practice.

195
00:21:05,221 --> 00:21:10,770
We do this by getting to know what effort feels like as a moment to moment experience.

196
00:21:10,790 --> 00:21:11,672
Are we slumping?

197
00:21:12,673 --> 00:21:14,757
If so, can we straighten up?

198
00:21:14,777 --> 00:21:18,743
Are we slacking, letting ourselves be carried away on every stray thought?

199
00:21:19,704 --> 00:21:22,128
If so, can we resolve to be mindful?

200
00:21:23,797 --> 00:21:46,210
over effort is a problem for many of us we want to be enlightened now this minute can we relax remember this is a gradual path and that we can learn to enjoy the journey if we can't relax can we feel the tensions that the experience of over effort itself become the focus for meditation

201
00:21:47,506 --> 00:21:59,810
As we stumble between slacking and over-effort, mindfulness guides us towards right effort, where we're alert and interested, but not hoping to gain anything from meditation.

202
00:22:00,634 --> 00:22:08,403
In time, that balance becomes more motivating than the false hopes of over effort, the dozy delight of slacking.

203
00:22:09,605 --> 00:22:13,670
As we develop right effort in meditation, we can apply it in practice.

204
00:22:14,431 --> 00:22:20,978
First, we have the here and now effort to prevent harmful states like greed and ill will arising.

205
00:22:21,659 --> 00:22:28,007
If we maintain mindfulness, the hindrances don't get a chance to blossom and spread their seeds.

206
00:22:28,027 --> 00:22:29,307
It's as simple as that.

207
00:22:30,452 --> 00:22:35,098
But sadly, we forget to be mindful a lot of the time in daily life.

208
00:22:35,118 --> 00:22:38,442
It's often pain of one form or another that wakes us up.

209
00:22:39,003 --> 00:22:47,255
Pain, whether emotional or physical, can stir fear, anxiety, worry, anger, blame, despair.

210
00:22:47,275 --> 00:22:51,220
It's easy to make a bad situation worse.

211
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:58,890
If we can remember this strand of right effort, the need to prevent unwholesome states from arising,

212
00:22:59,089 --> 00:23:06,219
We will bring mindfulness to the forefront, contain the negativity, prevent the negative spiral.

213
00:23:08,301 --> 00:23:12,567
It's especially important to make this effort during a busy day.

214
00:23:12,846 --> 00:23:19,596
Otherwise, minor irritations and frustrations build up and we might up saying something hurtful, spoiling a friendship.

215
00:23:21,179 --> 00:23:31,907
We could follow the practice of three-minute breathing spaces, which are a part of Jon Kabat-Zinn's mindfulness-based stress reduction programme.

216
00:23:31,928 --> 00:23:37,173
First, we acknowledge how we feel, let the emotions settle as we track them mindfully.

217
00:23:37,894 --> 00:23:49,683
We then follow the breath for a minute and end by reminding ourselves of the larger picture and whatever task or activity it is we're about to resume as we move back into this mindfully.

218
00:23:51,165 --> 00:24:04,298
We can also use right effort in the broader sense, choosing directions in life which will minimise laziness, aggression, meanness, all our worst characteristics, while encouraging our positive qualities.

219
00:24:04,952 --> 00:24:17,265
Many people report that life made a turn for the better when they started meditation practice and found Sangha friends, which naturally led to Dhamma study and regular retreats.

220
00:24:17,285 --> 00:24:25,633
These supportive conditions bring out the best in us, take the rough edges off our worst traits.

221
00:24:25,653 --> 00:24:32,199
Finally, we have the here and now effort to develop and make the most of our wholesome qualities.

222
00:24:32,219 --> 00:24:33,980
Meditation is the key.

223
00:24:34,432 --> 00:25:02,060
vipassana strengthens equanimity joy and all the factors of enlightenment while meta trains us to see the good in others and the good in ourselves next we have right mindfulness and for this i thought it would be interesting to go through the buddhism bites on full awareness in the teaching known as the four foundations for mindfulness the satipatthana sutta here's the quotation

224
00:25:03,391 --> 00:25:24,453
One acts in full awareness when going forward and returning, when looking ahead and looking away, when flexing and extending the limbs, when eating, drinking, defecating and urinating, walking, standing, sitting, falling, sleep, waking up, talking and keeping silent.

225
00:25:26,777 --> 00:25:30,681
Basically, we are to be fully aware in all aspects of life

226
00:25:31,166 --> 00:25:33,410
every moment of every day.

227
00:25:33,450 --> 00:25:42,480
Full awareness requires a broad understanding of our actions, as well as registering our moment to moment experience.

228
00:25:43,402 --> 00:25:45,805
Say we're walking to a neighbour's house.

229
00:25:45,825 --> 00:25:50,131
We could be mindful of the physical sensations of walking to keep us in the present moment.

230
00:25:50,971 --> 00:25:54,717
For full awareness, the context must also be borne in mind.

231
00:25:55,156 --> 00:25:57,359
We are going to visit our neighbour.

232
00:25:59,280 --> 00:26:11,640
While en route to work in the morning, we can remind ourselves regularly that we are indeed on our way to work, not to Shangri-La or wherever our daydreams are leading us.

233
00:26:11,660 --> 00:26:18,471
Instead of the detailed note we use for Mahasi retreat practice, broad brush phrases work better here.

234
00:26:18,931 --> 00:26:23,218
We can note, going to work, going to work.

235
00:26:23,238 --> 00:26:27,684
Sounds obvious, but how easy it is to forget the bigger picture.

236
00:26:28,609 --> 00:26:36,201
We go to work on autopilot, so familiar with every step of the journey that we can devote our time to worrying or daydreaming.

237
00:26:37,263 --> 00:26:45,856
The note, going to work, lifts us out of the doldrums, lets us feel more purposeful, helps us appreciate our surroundings.

238
00:26:46,999 --> 00:26:53,789
Within that broad awareness, we keep track of body movements like walking, reaching out, turning and so on.

239
00:26:55,271 --> 00:26:59,883
It can be a challenge to include inner and outer realities.

240
00:26:59,903 --> 00:27:04,755
At times we want to withdraw, abandon worldly cares, just breathe.

241
00:27:05,395 --> 00:27:12,031
At other times our attention is totally external, fascinated by whatever is happening around us.

242
00:27:12,198 --> 00:27:24,498
The challenge is to keep both worlds in mind, to include body awareness when entranced by the external world, to remember the broader context when our attention is pulled within.

243
00:27:25,980 --> 00:27:30,407
Reminding ourselves of the broader context can expose hidden emotions.

244
00:27:30,969 --> 00:27:38,121
We might be reluctant to note going to work, for example, but later in the day be quite happy to note going home.

245
00:27:39,805 --> 00:27:43,669
The reluctance indicates some negativity about work.

246
00:27:43,689 --> 00:27:49,295
If we don't make the note, that negativity might later sneak out as coldness or irritation.

247
00:27:50,096 --> 00:27:54,200
Unwittingly, we alienate our colleagues and make the situation worse.

248
00:27:55,101 --> 00:28:00,426
The note going to work shows us the weariness or anxiety or depression.

249
00:28:01,968 --> 00:28:05,711
Although it might feel worse than heading for the job on autopilot,

250
00:28:05,928 --> 00:28:09,733
Bearing with the feelings means the negativity can be acknowledged.

251
00:28:10,536 --> 00:28:14,602
Imperceptibly, perhaps our working life gets easier as a result.

252
00:28:15,963 --> 00:28:23,076
Even for less emotionally charged activities, the experience of going forward can differ from returning.

253
00:28:23,478 --> 00:28:26,781
Say I have to nip down to the shops for groceries.

254
00:28:26,801 --> 00:28:29,104
I'm often bright and purposeful on the way out.

255
00:28:29,644 --> 00:28:33,068
My step is light and I look with interest at the neighbour's garden.

256
00:28:33,869 --> 00:28:38,214
Coming home, my steps are more plodding, my eyes downcast.

257
00:28:38,715 --> 00:28:41,618
What I'm seeing here is the dukkha of transient.

258
00:28:42,319 --> 00:28:47,005
Each new activity offers a glimmer of hope that this world can make us happy.

259
00:28:47,575 --> 00:28:58,671
But when the choice between apples and oranges, biscuits and cake have been made and all the money spent, it becomes clear that my shopping spree has not delivered the goods I was secretly hoping for.

260
00:28:59,873 --> 00:29:01,214
The pattern can vary.

261
00:29:01,736 --> 00:29:06,603
For instance, the prospect of meeting friends may find us brighter on the way home than heading out.

262
00:29:07,223 --> 00:29:12,991
Worthwhile noting that it helps us to appreciate our friends when we see how they lift our mood.

263
00:29:14,288 --> 00:29:19,237
The second task is to be fully aware when looking ahead and looking away.

264
00:29:19,897 --> 00:29:23,183
Looking ahead reminds us of our destination, our purpose.

265
00:29:23,925 --> 00:29:27,412
So it helps with the broad context aspect of full awareness.

266
00:29:28,193 --> 00:29:37,730
When we look at anything deliberately, we can also interpret this as looking ahead, even if our head is turning aside to look at something on our left or right.

267
00:29:38,977 --> 00:29:44,865
While looking ahead is often stimulating, looking away often carries subtle dukkha.

268
00:29:44,885 --> 00:29:53,678
A friend practising mindfulness of speech found that her head turned slightly to one side when reacting against what another person was saying.

269
00:29:54,660 --> 00:30:00,347
Once she had detected the pattern, she was then able to use this as a wake-up call to notice a version.

270
00:30:01,048 --> 00:30:04,713
Her communication could then be much more honest and straightforward.

271
00:30:05,722 --> 00:30:11,471
Becoming mindful of looking ahead and away can tune us into the subtle dukkha of transience.

272
00:30:12,152 --> 00:30:17,720
Maybe the daffodils in a neighbour's garden take our fancy and we spend a moment looking at them.

273
00:30:17,740 --> 00:30:20,983
Then we look away, seeking out the next visual treat.

274
00:30:22,026 --> 00:30:25,170
Without registering it, we've tired of the daffodils.

275
00:30:26,332 --> 00:30:30,076
These persistent, minor disappointments promote cynicism.

276
00:30:30,698 --> 00:30:33,059
The world is full of false promises.

277
00:30:33,721 --> 00:30:35,742
Everything lets us down in the end.

278
00:30:36,663 --> 00:30:47,154
But if we prime ourselves to be mindful of looking ahead and looking away, we may notice a subtle expectation in the former and disappointment in the latter.

279
00:30:47,955 --> 00:30:52,580
Over time, we learn that expectation and disappointment are of our own making.

280
00:30:53,122 --> 00:30:57,246
It's much easier to appreciate daffodils when we expect less of them.

281
00:30:59,757 --> 00:31:06,349
Our third task, flexing and extending the limbs, has less emotional significance.

282
00:31:06,369 --> 00:31:11,721
Instead, the action connects us with neutral experiences that we usually ignore.

283
00:31:12,362 --> 00:31:21,359
We flex and extend our limbs several times while we're washing, dressing, doing household chores, manual labour, opening doors, numerous other tasks.

284
00:31:21,744 --> 00:31:27,755
As we become mindful of these movements, we add bodily awareness to daily life.

285
00:31:27,775 --> 00:31:37,009
The body offers a restful focus for a mind that so easily hits overdrive, making grandiose plans and assuming we can do 10 things at once.

286
00:31:38,031 --> 00:31:44,461
If we put our bodies in the picture, we come down to earth and our plans and promises become more realistic.

287
00:31:45,758 --> 00:31:49,544
Outside of retreat, eating mindfully is often a challenge.

288
00:31:50,065 --> 00:31:56,413
The first spoonful might be savoured, but by the second we're already taking out our mobile phones.

289
00:31:57,134 --> 00:31:59,839
I find the need to set clear red lines here.

290
00:31:59,880 --> 00:32:05,548
No phones, books or entertainment other than the pleasure of mindful eating.

291
00:32:06,930 --> 00:32:12,558
This develops a prescient of joy or mudita, a joyful response to the good things in life.

292
00:32:14,429 --> 00:32:17,733
Eating and drinking brings us to urinating and defecating.

293
00:32:18,434 --> 00:32:22,180
The activities themselves are usually neutral experiences.

294
00:32:23,001 --> 00:32:25,945
It is the thought of what's happening that gets through.

295
00:32:26,507 --> 00:32:32,275
The social taboo around these essential bodily functions can result in embarrassment and shame.

296
00:32:33,016 --> 00:32:37,061
The way out, of course, is to feel and acknowledge the emotional baggage.

297
00:32:37,295 --> 00:32:47,098
This totally unnecessary shame will start to burn out and we develop a healthy respect for the body's ability to discard its waste.

298
00:32:48,542 --> 00:32:52,231
We can practice with the Buddha's guidance in many areas of daily life.

299
00:32:52,903 --> 00:32:59,490
During any journey, ideally from the start, we can pick a phrase like going to the shops and repeat this regularly.

300
00:32:59,930 --> 00:33:07,537
We can do the same on the way home, being curious as to whether the outward and homeward journeys feel the same or different.

301
00:33:08,377 --> 00:33:12,641
We can take an interest in what our eyes are doing and any emotional undertones.

302
00:33:13,122 --> 00:33:14,103
Are they looking ahead?

303
00:33:14,722 --> 00:33:17,346
Is there a sense of expectancy, interest?

304
00:33:18,026 --> 00:33:19,126
Or are they looking away?

305
00:33:19,166 --> 00:33:22,269
Is there a quiet judgment, disinterest?

306
00:33:22,789 --> 00:33:33,787
We can be mindful during communications, spotting when we feel hurt, bored or irritated by the conversation and when we feel buoyed up, interested or excited by the interaction.

307
00:33:36,951 --> 00:33:40,798
The final strand in the Eightfold Path is Right Concentration.

308
00:33:41,875 --> 00:33:49,365
We need to make time for formal meditation practice, where the mind can come to stillness, rest in present awareness.

309
00:33:50,205 --> 00:33:54,291
For this, we need to develop a habit of regular daily meditation.

310
00:33:54,932 --> 00:33:57,717
Some prefer mornings, some prefer evenings.

311
00:33:58,136 --> 00:34:00,099
If you can do both, ideal.

312
00:34:00,961 --> 00:34:02,383
How long to meditate for?

313
00:34:02,903 --> 00:34:07,630
That really depends on your circumstances, how many other demands there are in your times.

314
00:34:08,047 --> 00:34:09,853
If you can do an hour, excellent.

315
00:34:10,273 --> 00:34:14,807
But whatever is possible, 40 minutes, 30 minutes, whatever you can manage.

316
00:34:15,871 --> 00:34:18,338
It always helps if you can find support.

317
00:34:18,920 --> 00:34:21,306
Would anyone in your household meditate with you?

318
00:34:21,788 --> 00:34:23,172
Could you find a local group?

319
00:34:24,416 --> 00:34:37,255
The single most important factor in sustaining my meditation in the early years was the fact that I found a local group, got into the habit of meeting them every week for meditation and dam study discussion as well.

320
00:34:38,056 --> 00:34:43,184
They soon became my best friends and supported many aspects of the Eightfold Path.

321
00:34:44,717 --> 00:34:48,282
There are also lots of online options for support nowadays.

322
00:34:48,782 --> 00:34:54,389
For example, there is an online meditation hall that you can access via the Satipanya website.

323
00:34:54,849 --> 00:35:01,538
It's a Zoom link and open all day, but the only times you're likely to see others are 6am and 8pm.

324
00:35:02,219 --> 00:35:07,565
The 6am slot has an hour's meditation, followed by some chanting and metta practice.

325
00:35:08,106 --> 00:35:13,391
The 8pm slot has meditation, followed by metta and joy practices and chant.

326
00:35:15,498 --> 00:35:19,762
Retreats give the best support for developing concentration.

327
00:35:19,782 --> 00:35:31,673
We shut ourselves away from the world for a few days or a few weeks so that there isn't the continuous inflow of stimulation, views, demands, responsibilities that are part and parcel of everyday life.

328
00:35:32,434 --> 00:35:36,137
Retreat conditions give optimal support for right concentration.

329
00:35:36,617 --> 00:35:42,483
We learn to focus the mind, gather its energies, channel them in the direction of liberation.

330
00:35:44,472 --> 00:35:52,860
Concentration is an unfortunate translation for the Pali word samadhi, which conveys a sense of restfulness rather than forcing.

331
00:35:53,561 --> 00:35:58,105
We're resting attention on some aspect of present experience.

332
00:35:58,806 --> 00:36:01,407
We have the analogy of a bee searching for honey.

333
00:36:02,108 --> 00:36:04,891
First, she has to track a flower as it bobs around.

334
00:36:04,931 --> 00:36:14,039
This represents the first stage of concentration when we're making an effort to bring attention back to the breath whenever the mind wanders.

335
00:36:14,829 --> 00:36:20,960
Then the bee lands on the flower, is carried around by it, no longer has to make the effort to track.

336
00:36:21,740 --> 00:36:30,916
This is the second stage of concentration where our attention is riveted by the sensations and feelings of present experience.

337
00:36:32,137 --> 00:36:35,322
We no longer need that effort to direct attention.

338
00:36:35,943 --> 00:36:38,728
Mindfulness continues of its own accord.

339
00:36:40,530 --> 00:36:49,284
Just as the bee drinks nectar in these moments, we drink the nectar of direct experience, the intimate contact with reality.

340
00:36:50,405 --> 00:37:02,083
It's from direct experience that we learn the Dhamma for ourselves, convince ourselves of the Four Noble Truths and the other ways the Buddha expressed his understanding.

341
00:37:02,737 --> 00:37:27,074
so do make time for retreats in your life it can seem as though we're always too busy for this when i was working full-time i used planned retreats well in advance several months ahead when my diary was still empty that way i could give my family plenty of notice and say a clear no to whatever other demands came in during that period without letting people down

342
00:37:28,523 --> 00:37:39,061
I hope this resume of the Noble Eightfold Path helps you to see that there are many areas in life that can be developed of spiritual practice.

343
00:37:39,081 --> 00:37:42,347
To come back to one thing, the importance of support.

344
00:37:43,028 --> 00:37:46,795
Do make an effort to find friends who also want to walk this path.

345
00:37:47,396 --> 00:37:50,802
This is Sangha, spiritual friendship.

346
00:37:50,822 --> 00:37:52,405
Real life friends are best.

347
00:37:52,755 --> 00:37:54,398
But online also works well.

348
00:37:54,998 --> 00:37:56,701
I have a friend who lives in India.

349
00:37:56,740 --> 00:38:00,465
We regularly exchange Dhamma questions and comments by email.

350
00:38:01,447 --> 00:38:05,431
Our friends influence us and we in turn influence them.

351
00:38:06,793 --> 00:38:09,277
When we get despondent, they encourage us.

352
00:38:09,757 --> 00:38:14,963
When we're trying to pick our way through some thorny moral issue, we have someone to talk it over with.

353
00:38:15,744 --> 00:38:21,733
When Ananda, the Buddha's cousin and attendant, remarked that good friendship was half of the spiritual life,

354
00:38:22,117 --> 00:38:27,630
The Buddha replied that good friendship was the whole of spiritual life.

355
00:38:27,650 --> 00:38:37,072
May we all find the friendship and support we need to follow the Eightfold Path in our relationships, our work and all aspects of life.

